`SchemaOptions` is an object created for each operation of `SchemaDeclaration`. It can be used in the scope of `SchemaDeclaration` operation like the example below:

```javascript
schema.setQuery(function($) {
	// $ === SchemaOptions
});

schema.setSave(function($) {
	// $ === SchemaOptions
});

schema.addWorkflow('send', function($) {
	// $ === SchemaOptions
});```

methods.body:
Adds some `SchemaDeclaration` operation as a next operation after current operation in chaining `SchemaInstance.$async()`.

```javascript
$.next('workflow', 'send');

// or
$.next('workflow', 'send', { some_key: 'with custom options' });

// or
$.next('save', { rewrite: true, message: 'this is custom options' });```
It's alias for `$.model.$next()`.

Adds some `SchemaDeclaration` operation onto end of chaining of `SchemaInstance.$async()`.

```javascript
$.push('workflow', 'send');

// or
$.push('workflow', 'send', { some_key: 'with custom options' });

// or
$.push('save', { rewrite: true, message: 'this is custom options' });```
It's alias for `$.model.$push()`.

It can be used for one-line async operations. It returns `SUCCESS()` result if the callback doesn't return error. A simple usage: 

```javascript
// Returns SUCCESS(true)
NOSQL('users').remove().where('id', '9289').callback($.done());

// Returns SUCCESS(true, response_from_callback)
NOSQL('users').remove().where('id', '9289').callback($.done(true));```

Fast and simple error handling. It wraps this code `$.error.push()` and executes `$.callback()` immediately. A simple usage: 

```javascript
if (!$.model.terms) {
    $.invalid('terms', 'You must agree with terms and conditions.');
    return;
}```

It can write/read a value from model repository (internal meta-data repository contains each SchemaInstance object). A simple usage: 

```javascript
// Writing
$.repository('custom', 'value');

// Reading
console.log($.repository('custom'));```

api.body:
`Chunker` is a very helpful tool for storing temporary data when you are importing some data from another services or databases. It can store defined count of documents/data (serialized in JSON) per file and after import is done you can browse data step-by-step. `Chunker` is defined in `FrameworkUtils` and here is a simple usage:

```javascript
var chunker = U.chunker('products', 50);

// chunker === instance

somestream.on('data', U.streamer('<product>', '</product>', function(value, index) {
	var product = value.parseXML();

	// The chunker creates multiple files with a maximum count of chunks (in this case: 50 products)
	chunker.write(product);

	// Here we can't wait for DB because data are flowing in this time
}));

somestream.on('end', function() {

	// Flushs buffer
	chunker.end();

	chunker.each(function(items, next, index) {

		console.log(chunker.percentage);

		// here we can update DB

		// ....
		// ....

		// Read next items
		next();

	}, function() {

		// This method is called when the chunker doesn't contain any other items (optional).

		// Cleans up hdd (removes files) and memory
		chunker.destroy();
	});

});
```

__IMPORTANT__:
Chunker stores items to different files. A chunker `name` is a name of the file. When the chunker is destroyed then it removes all files automatically.

pages.body:
Controllers are responsible for responding to requests from a web browser, mobile application or any other system capable of communicating with a server. Each route is mapped into the action and the action responds to requests. The controllers with modules are the main feature of the framework logic.

```plain
Framework initialization:

01. Bundles
02. Modules
03. Packages
04. Models
05. Schemas
06. Operations
07. Themes
08. Definitions
09. Controllers
10. Components
```

The controller __knows 3x types of routes__: _classic_, _websocket_ and _file route_.

- The classic route handles a classic requests into the dynamic content (view engine).
- The websocket route handles WebSockets connections.
- The file route handles static files.

---

__More informations__

- The controller is the plain JavaScript file with `.js` extension.
- The framework automatically loads the controller into the memory.
- All controllers are stored in `your-app/controllers/` directory.
- `exports.install` is executed automatically and one time.
- Views are loaded according to the controller name `your-app/views/your-controller-name/`.
- You can create unlimited number of controllers.
- The controller can be injected from the URL address, [example](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-install-controller).
- Routing supports routing according to the subdomains, [example](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/routing-subdomain).
- The controller can communicate with the other controller.

---

## Examples

Following [examples](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/) contain controllers.

- [Example: Routing](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/routing)
- [Example: Routing + Flags](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/routing-flags)
- [Example: Routing + Flags + Roles](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/routing-flags-roles)
- [Example: Routing + Generators](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/routing-generators)
- [Example: Inline routing](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/routing-inline)
- [Example: Image resizer routing](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/routing-resize)
- [Example: Subdomain routing](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/routing-subdomain)
- [Example: Routing timeout](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/routing-timeout)
- [Example: WebSocket routing](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/websocket)
- [Example: Cancel executing action in controller](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/controller-cancel)
- [Example: Sending email from action in controller](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/controller-mail)
- [Example: Cache output from action in controller](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/controller-memorize)
- [Example: Communicating between controllers between different web apps](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/controller-proxy)
- [Example: Transfer request to different action](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/controller-transfer)
- [Example: Install controller from URL](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-install-controller)

---

## The definition

- Instance of: [FrameworkController](#api~FrameworkController)

### PROPERTY: exports.id;

`optional` Can contain only the controller name (it's the identificator name). A __default value__ for this property is the controller filename without extension.

```javascript
exports.id = 'Controller name';
```

### METHOD: exports.install;

`optional` `important` This is the initialization function of the controller.

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
	ROUTE('/');
	ROUTE('/api/{type}/', json_api, ['put']);
	WEBSOCKET('/chat/', json_websocket_chat, ['json']);

	// or
	F.restful('/users/', action_query, action_read, action_save, action_remove);
};
```

### METHOD: exports.uninstall;

`optional` This function is executed when the framework is uninstalled from the framework.

```javascript
exports.uninstall = function() {
	console.log('This controller is uninstalled.');
};
```

### METHOD: exports.usage;

`optional` This function is used for debug purposes and should return an object which summarises the internal state of your module. [Example: Usage](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-usage). Tip: You can use F.usage() to iterate the exports.usage() of all active modules.

```javascript
exports.usage = function() {
	return { requests: counter };
};
```

### A full example of the controller

Filename: `controllers/default.js`

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
	ROUTE('/', view_index);
	ROUTE('/contact/', view_contact);
	ROUTE('/hello/', plain_hello);
	ROUTE('/api/codelist/', json_codelist, ['xhr', 'get']);
	ROUTE('/sync/', view_sync);
};

function view_index() {
	var self = this;
	self.view('index');
}

function view_contact() {
	var self = this;
	self.layout('layouts/subpage');
	self.view('contact', { email: '@' });
}

function plain_hello() {
	var self = this;
	self.plain('Hello world!');
}

function json_codelist() {
	var self = this;
	self.mail('info@company.com', 'Codelist notifications', 'mails/codelist');
	self.json([1, 2, 3, 4, 5]);
}

// GENERATORS
function *view_sync() {
	var self = this;
	var users = yield sync(DATABASE('users').$$all(n => n))();
	self.json(users);
}

// or an inline route
ROUTE('/services/', function() {
	var self = this;
	self.view('services');
});
```

## The routing

- Method: [F.route()](#api~Framework~F.route)
- Method: [framework.websocket()](#api~Framework~framework.websocket)
- Method: [framework.file()](#api~Framework~framework.file)
- List: [route flags](#api~HttpRouteOptionsFlags)

### System routing

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
	ROUTE('#400', custom); // Bad Request
	ROUTE('#401', custom); // Unauthorized
	ROUTE('#403', custom); // Forbidden
	ROUTE('#404', custom); // Not Found
	ROUTE('#408', custom); // Request Timeout
	ROUTE('#409', custom); // Conflict
	ROUTE('#431', custom); // Request Header Fields Too Large
	ROUTE('#500', custom); // Internal Server Error
	ROUTE('#501', custom); // Not Implemented
}

function custom() {
	this.view('http-error-view');
}```

