</script>
```

__Create `/components/newsletter.js`__ (server-side):

```javascript
// +v2.5.0 optional
exports.group = 'Name of group';

exports.install = function() {
	F.route('/api/newsletter/', json_newsletter, ['post']);
};

function json_newsletter() {
	var self = this;
	self.body.ip = self.ip;
	self.body.created = F.datetime;
	NOSQL('newsletter').insert(self.body);
	self.json(SUCCESS(true));
}
```

__Rendering__:

```html
<h2>Newsletter 1</h2>
@{component('newsletter')}

<h2>Newsletter 2</h2>
@{component('newsletter')}
```

__Rendering all components by Group name__:

```html
<h2>Renders all components from the group</h2>
@{components('Name of group')}
```

## Good to know

### Static files according to group name

Total.js `v2.7.0` supports rendering of specific scripts/styles for component's group, for example:

```html
@{components('dashboard')}
@{components('flowboard')}
```

__The framework will render__:

```html
<head>
	<link rel="stylesheet" href="/components.css?group=dashboard&version=1498544518093" />
	<script src="/components.js?group=dashboard&version=1498544518093"></script>
	<link rel="stylesheet" href="/components.css?group=flowboard&version=1498544518093" />
	<script src="/components.js?group=flowboard&version=1498544518093"></script>
</head>
```

If the view contains `@{component()}` the framework renders static files (js+css) from all registered components.

### Hash

Because of HTTP cache, when the framework registers a new component it changes version hash. Therefore your `components.css` and `components.js` have still another hash e.g. `?version=ak38s`.

### Renaming of static files

You can rename static files `.css` and `.js` of components via config file:

__Default settings__:

```html
static-url-components    : /components.
```

__You can change it to e.g.__:

```html
static-url-components    : /components/all.
```

__The result will be:__
- `/components/all.js`
- `/components/all.css`

Total.js has a simple authorization mechanism. It's built on one delegate function `F.onAuthorize` or `AUTH(function)`. The authorization is asynchronous.

- You can create your own authorization mechanism (Total.js gives open options).
- The authorization delegate is async.
- You can authorize users according to the cookies / headers.
- You can set user roles.
- The authorization delegate adds `authorize` and `unauthorize` flag according to the state.
- Is executed in each request.
- __Delegate does not handle static files.__
- [Example: authorization](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/authorization)
- [Download module: Auth](https://github.com/totaljs/modules/tree/master/Security/auth)

---

![Authorization](resources/authorization.png)

---

## Simple example

Create e.g. definition:

```javascript
AUTH(function(req, res, flags, next) {

	// EXAMPLE:
	var userId = req.cookie('user').parseInt();

	if (userId === 0) {
		// unauthorized user
		next(false);
		return;
	}

	var nosql = NOSQL('users');

	nosql.one().where('id', userId).callback(function(err, user) {

		if (err || !user) {
			// unauthorized user
			next(false);
			return;
		}

		// user is authorized
		next(true, user);

		// or assign the user object to request.user:
		/*
			req.user = user;
			next(true);
		*/
	});
});
```

Usage in controllers:

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
	ROUTE('/user/', view_logged,   ['authorize']);
	ROUTE('/user/', view_unlogged, ['unauthorize']);
}

function view_logged() {
	this.view('logged');
}

function view_unlogged() {
	this.view('unlogged');
}```

Schemas are a big part of Total.js framework. With schemas you can control incoming data and convert them to your defined types. Each schema can support validation and multiple operations (CRUD operations, transformations, workflows or hooks) which you can call step-by-step.

## Creating schemas

A schema describes a data-types/data-structure for incoming data only and __schema isn't a mirror for database table schema__. So we define a simple schema `User` which we use on this page:

```javascript
NEWSCHEMA('User', function(schema) {

	// Define fields in the schema
	// schema.define('FIELD_NAME', 'DATA_TYPE', [required]);

	schema.define('firstname', 'Capitalize(30)', true);
	schema.define('lastname', 'Capitalize(30)', true);
	schema.define('age', Number, age => age >= 18);

	// Define operations in the schema
	// BTW: all operations below are optional

	schema.setQuery(function($) {
		// $ ==> is SchemaOptions
		// your code
		$.success();
	});

	schema.setGet(function($) {
		// $ ==> is SchemaOptions
		// your code
		$.success();
	});

	schema.setInsert(function($) {
		// $ ==> is SchemaOptions
		// your code
		// $.model ==> data
		$.success();
	});

	schema.setUpdate(function($) {
		// $ ==> is SchemaOptions
		// your code
		// $.model ==> data
		$.success();
	});

	schema.setRemove(function($) {
		// $ ==> is SchemaOptions
		// your code
		$.success();
	});

	schema.addWorkflow('logoff', function($) {
		// $ ==> is SchemaOptions
		// your code
		$.success();
	});

	// etc..

});
```

Framework converts incoming data according to the schema __always__. So you __always__ get type as you defined. Default values:

- `array` returns `[]`
- `boolean` returns `false`
- `date` returns `new Date()`
- `json` returns `''`
- `number` returns `0`
- `object` returns `null`
- `string` returns `''`
- `email` returns `'@'`
- link to schema returns `null`

__Good to know__:

- schema doesn't need to contain defined operations
- schema doesn't need to contain defined fields (e.g. you want to use operations only)
- all [schema data-types](#)
- methods and properties in [SchemaOptions](#)
- methods in [SchemaInstance](#)

---

## Dictionary

### SchemaDeclaration

- [Documentation](#)

```javascript
NEWSCHEMA('User', function(schema) {
	// schema ===  SchemaDeclaration
});
```

### SchemaOptions

`SchemaOptions` can be a part in some Schema operation.

- [Documentation](#)

```javascript
NEWSCHEMA('User', function(schema) {

	schema.setInsert(function($) {
		// $ === SchemaOptions
	});

	schema.addWorkflow('something', function($) {
		// $ === SchemaOptions
	});

});
```

### SchemaInstance

This is an instance generated according to the `SchemaDeclaration`.

- [Documentation](#)

__Created in the schema__:

```javascript
NEWSCHEMA('User', function(schema) {

	// YOUR SCHEMA DECLARATION
	// ...
	// ...
	// ...

	var user = schema.create();
	// user === SchemaInstance

});
```

__Created manually__:

```javascript
var user = $CREATE('User');
// user === SchemaInstance
```

__In controllers__:

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
	ROUTE('POST /api/users/', action, ['*User'];
};

function action() {
	var self = this;        // this === controller
	var user = self.model;  // this.model === SchemaInstance
}
```

## Using schemas in routing

Imaging that the code below is a part of some controller:

```javascript
exports.install = function() {

	ROUTE('GET     /api/users/',        ['*User --> @query']);
	// Framework calls this defined operation automatically: "User.setQuery(...)"

	ROUTE('GET     /api/users/{id}/',   ['*User --> @get']);
	// Framework calls this defined operation automatically: "User.setGet(...)"

	ROUTE('DELETE  /api/users/{id}/',   ['*User --> @remove']);
	// Framework calls this defined operation automatically: "User.setRemove(...)"

	ROUTE('POST    /api/users/',        ['*User --> @insert']);
	// Framework calls this defined operation automatically: "User.setInsert(...)"
	// Incoming data will be validated

	ROUTE('PUT     /api/users/{id}/',   ['*User --> @update']);
	// Framework calls this defined operation automatically: "User.setUpdate(...)"
	// Incoming data will be validated

	ROUTE('GET     /api/users/logoff/', ['*User --> @logoff']);
	// Framework calls this defined workflow automatically: "User.addWorkflow('logoff', ...)"

};
```

## Using schemas globally

Schemas can be used everywhere in your code and we have prepared several methods:

```javascript
// $INSERT(schema_name, model, [options], [callback], [controller]);
// Performs schema.setInsert()
$INSERT('User', { firstname: 'Peter', lastname: 'Širka', age: 18 }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});

// $UPDATE(schema_name, model, [options], [callback], [controller]);
// Performs schema.setUpdate()
$UPDATE('User', { firstname: 'Peter', lastname: 'Širka', age: 18 }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});

// $SAVE(schema_name, model, [options], [callback], [controller]);
// Performs schema.setSave()
$SAVE('User', { firstname: 'Peter', lastname: 'Širka', age: 18 }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});

// $REMOVE(schema_name, [options], [callback], [controller]);
// Performs schema.setQuery()
$REMOVE('User', { id: 101 }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});

// $QUERY(schema_name, [options], [callback], [controller]);
// Performs schema.setQuery()
$QUERY('User', { take: 10 }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});

// $GET(schema_name, [options], [callback], [controller]);
// Performs schema.setGet()
$GET('User', { id: 100 }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});

// $WORKFLOW(schema_name, [options], [callback], [controller]);
// Performs schema.addWorkflow('send', ...);
$WORKFLOW('User', 'send', { id: 100 }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});

// $TRANSFORM(schema_name, [options], [callback], [controller]);
// Performs schema.addTransform('xml', ...);
$TRANSFORM('User', 'xml', { indent: true }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});
```

